I've eaten at the restaurant before, but never got around to reviewing it. But recently had Brenda's through delivery. Surprisingly, the quality is just as good after a little traveling! Chicken Etouffée: Loved the combination of the thick gravy and tender chicken. Just the type of hearty meal to warm you up on a chilly San Francisco day. Some nice Southern spices, but not overdoing it. The rice was already mixed into the etouffée; it paired well but I kinda wish it was given separately so I could choose the rice-to-etouffée recipe that suited me best. 3-Piece BFC Special: I got the breast & wing platter, but added a drumstick. All my favorite pieces for fried chicken! Each piece had a very crispy skin, which stayed crispy through delivery, and tons of moist chicken underneath. Had a little spice going, but the ample packets of Crystal hot sauce was a good addition too. I could easily eat a whole bucket of this stuff! Biscuit: A tad dry. The outer edges were very brittle and broke off with a slight touch. Not sure if it was by design or a tadold. Thank goodness there was some yummy jam to moisten it up!

Got here around 2:40pm on a Monday afternoon and luckily they still seated us! Ordered the beignet flight, cup of gumbo, and fried chicken Benedict for two. The beignets were all DIVINE, crispy on the outside and fluffy on the inside, and the sweetness level was just right. I loved each flavor so so so much, but as someone who loves apple pie, the apple beignet was my favorite! Would make the trip from San Jose just for these beignets, cannot stress enough how delicious they were!! The gumbo was good and not too salty. The biscuit on the Benedict was fluffy and flaky like everyone else has been saying. I understand why they have 10k reviews now. Amazing and a must-try SF restaurant!

Was expecting more with all the reviews but nothing really blew my mind away with the Benedict with fried chicken and hash. Portions are huge, wish I would've had room for the beignets! They looked delicious and almost every table around me had a plate. Went on a Tuesday morning around 10am, no wait.

I think the last time I dined here was 5 years ago! I was a frequent customer when I was in my beignet phase in life. Hahaha. Needless to say, it is still busy to this day. My go to orders are the crawfish beignet. It's bomb! A must starter to your meal. The flight is nice to have if you want some variety of sweetness, but the chocolate and the apple is an easy pass. (Nothing special in my opinion) I always order the watermelon sweet tea and my usual order is the hangtown fry - oysters omelette and I substitute to make sure I get the fluffy biscuit. Biscuits and butter! Bomb! I have tried the po boy sammies, the fried chicken, the shrimp and grits, the grillades and grits, and everything is a must try. Very rich and satisfying! The parking in the area is a bit hard. I have had to circled around the block many times. When it's a for sure busy day, I'll drop someone off to put our name on the list. With luck, I'll snag a spot and still be able to make it back just in time to be seated!

Brenda's is one of my go-to's for brunch! They never disappoint as long as you know what to order. Also if you know how to beat the line. I work down the street so on weekdays, if you go around 11am, you're perfectly ahead of the noontime rush, and will be seated right away. You can also always do a pickup order, if you don't care to dine within. Food is just as good. Also if you're into their crawfish beignets (which everyone should be!), you can grab something similar from their little neighbor shop that sells quick bites. The seating inside is a bit cramped, but not too bad. The restaurant is decently maintained in terms of cleanliness. Service is pretty good and decently fast. I've come here a few times and have tried a number of items. All of which have been good: Eggs Benedict- comes on a biscuit instead of an english muffin and OMG these biscuits are so good. I normally dont like biscuits but I love theirs! Made in house and just deliciously crispy but soft inside, they are the perfect pair with the eggs. I've ordered this with their Fried Chicken, which you can't go wrong with. And also their Pulled Pork which was tender and seasoned well. Beignet Flight- Their sweet beignets are a pretty good treat if you're craving dessert, but their crawfish beignets steal the show. Even though sometimes it can have a slightly strong seafood taste, the cajun spices are so savory, and the exterior dough so comforting. The crawfish beignets are such a treat, and so unique to this restaurant, you have to order them everytime you come! Hangtown Fry- Worth trying once for the oysters, but I wouldn't order it again. The oysters kinda give an off taste to the dish and its overall not too pleasing. Too fishy, I guess? Not sure if its on the menu anymore, but I have also tried their Gumbo and it was nothing special. you can skip this.

Brenda's French Soul Food has been on my radar for a while and I'm so glad I finally got a chance to dine here this past weekend. My boyfriend and I went to the city to visit my cousin and his girlfriend, and we opted to have a late lunch here. We arrived around 1:15pm and added our name for a table for 4 on the chalkboard waitlist. We asked for some menus to decide on what we wanted while we waited and hung out outside until our group was called. After about a 25 minute wait, we were seated, and our orders were taken soon after since we let our waitress know that we were ready to order. Our drinks (watermelon sweet tea and molasses iced coffee) came out really quickly, along with iced waters for everyone. Not long after, our order came: - Shrimp & grits - Fried chicken eggs benedict - Molasses pork chop special (eggs over medium) - Crawfish beignets We all shared and sampled each other's orders, and I can honestly say that I couldn't pick a favorite - they were all so delicious! I definitely understand the hype. Everything tasted really fresh and packed full of flavor. I'd highly recommend the visit here, although I'd suggest visiting during an in-between meal time to lessen the wait time. Also keep in mind - this restaurant isn't super huge inside, so it's probably not ideal for larger groups. Most of the parties dining around us were groups of 2 or 3. All in all, a great stop for brunch/lunch for delicious food!

BRENDA'S SOUL FOOD IS TO DIE FOR. Please come if you're craving extraordinary brunch food. We ordered the Florentine egg Benedict and it was pretty life changing. The 2 eggs come on a cream biscuit that was amazing and fluffy but also had a nice crisp when you bite into it. The eggs were perfectly cooked and the sauce was perfect. The potatoes were a nice hash (the other option was grits!) and it was good. My friend and I shared it and it was the perfect portion size paired with the apple beignets. We also got the house coffee with chicory that was amazing paired with it. Might we also add that after ordering the Florentine eggs Benedicts, they only took 5 minutes to make?! It was amazing.

7/27/19 I think pretty much every other day in my Yelp feed I see someone's pics or review of this place. Why did it take me so goddam long to come???... I got no excuse. But, hey, I did, and I tell you, the hype is real, and absolutely deserved! Yeah, I've been to 'Nawlins (a few times even) and got fatter. Definitely fatter. So the food's good and all, but Brenda's makes the stuff so much easier to eat for those that don't wanna get diabetes or die of a heart attack, or before being able to blind people with the solar reflector your male pattern baldness could be. Don't get me wrong, if you eat this crap every day you're still gonna die before your friends, but... at least you're gonna live longer in bliss... 1. Community Coffee with Chicory $3: K, so I've only had coffee with chicory maybe at most a couple times in my life, so I dunno if I'm qualified to judge this one, but all I can say it has a very interesting taste with powerful flavors at first, though not bitter. But give it a few seconds, cause the finish is bitter as f. Quite the experience. 8/10? 2. Grandma's Molasses-Black Walnut Iced Coffee $5 "with whipped cream": And like the hot coffee, definitely interesting. It's certainly sweet, as you'd expect, but there some good complexity going on in there. There's of course a very small hint of walnut, but the molasses adds the sweetness that balances with the slightly acidic fruity flavors. I liked it. 8/10 3. Beignet Flight $12 "can't decide? try a sampling of each! four per order"... 3a. Plain "for the die-hard traditionalist": Alright, so we gotta compare with the standard: Cafe Du Monde's. Besides the obvious, being Brenda's is not absolutely encased in sugar, I remember Du Monde's being stretchier, a bit chewier, and airier (check out my pics for the place, including one where we stretch one apart--quite impressive.) But that's not to say Brenda's is bad. Oh no!... it's delicious! Moist, slightly denser, and with a great savory and slightly crisp crust. Definitely technically great. 9/10 3b. Chocolate "filled with molten Ghirardelli chocolate": So, the rest of the beignets we had follow the same formula: the same dough and cooking, same flesh and crisp finish, except the dough only serves to surround the filling, which takes up 80%ish of the total volume. In this case, sure enough, that's some really insanely INTENSE bloody chocolate! DAMN. Dark, supremely concentrated... thick, cause thick is the way we all like it, most of the times... alright, I gotta say, that thick and dark ain't my thing, but maybe it's yours... 9/10 3c. Granny Smith Apple "sweetened with cinnamon-honey butter": This was the only variation I didn't like. Despite what their description implies, this thing is barely sweet. Don't expect anything like your mom's apple pie here with oozing goodness. It just ain't that. 5/10 3d. Crawfish "spiced with cayenne, scallions & cheddar": GENIUS. Fried dough. Creamy seafood. Cheese. Did I say FRIED? Yup. Lucky there ain't no Brenda's in San Jose cause I'd just eat these everyday, ...and die. 10/10 4. Shrimp & Grits $17 "sauteed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy": Ah, and so finally a quintessential 'Nawlins dish!--and I think the chef is most in her element with this one. Starting with the grits, they're almost kinda soupy. this ain't no Roscoe's grits. And it probably ain't like most grits you've had--only naturally creamy, with all the flavor coming from that red sauce. And that red sauce--it's remarkably NOT oily! Like you almost cannot see any grease whatsoever. It's almost inevitable there's a film of orange oil (we're not eating Szechuan are we???), but Brenda's is remarkably CLEAN. And interesting thing though, the sauce is sweet. I dunno how I feel about that, but anyway... it's different and not offensive in that way. So, you look at that dish and go... wtf... I see like... 2, maybe 3 shrimps poking through? Well, after I start diving in, I tell you, the shrimp is ENDLESS! Personally I think the plating is just too understated in how all the shrimp is hidden underneath... all that PERFECTLY cooked shrimp. Not dry, not stringy, still a bit translucent and crunchy. Yummy! This has got to be the least greasy, most wholesome shrimp and grits I've ever had, yet somehow it's still rich as f. A gastronomic miracle. 10/10 5. Chicken, Sausage & Okra Gumbo (Cup) $6: And like the shrimp & grits, that wholesome-homesome shows through here too. The "soup" is slightly less thick than what you'll find elsewhere, and the seasoning is definitely far more tame, yet everything seems just right and balanced. The chicken is in big chunks, and NOT DRY. Everything's just so CLEAN..... almost refreshingly simple and light! For a gumbo!!! 10/10 I cannot wait to come back, but definitely for dinner! 5/5 #soulfood #southernfood #southerncuisine #cajun #creole #star #sanfrancisco

    I've eaten at the restaurant before, but never got around to reviewing it.  But recently had Brenda's through delivery.  Surprisingly, the quality is just as good after a little traveling!

    Chicken Etouffée: Loved the combination of the thick gravy and tender chicken.  Just the type of hearty meal to warm you up on a chilly San Francisco day.  Some nice Southern spices, but not overdoing it.  The rice was already mixed into the etouffée; it paired well but I kinda wish it was given separately so I could choose the rice-to-etouffée recipe that suited me best.

    3-Piece BFC Special: I got the breast & wing platter, but added a drumstick.  All my favorite pieces for fried chicken!  Each piece had a very crispy skin, which stayed crispy through delivery, and tons of moist chicken underneath.  Had a little spice going, but the ample packets of Crystal hot sauce was a good addition too.  I could easily eat a whole bucket of this stuff!

    Biscuit: A tad dry.  The outer edges were very brittle and broke off with a slight touch.  Not sure if it was by design or a tadold.  Thank goodness there was some yummy jam to moisten it up!

    Brenda's is one of my go-to's for brunch! They never disappoint as long as you know what to order. Also if you know how to beat the line. I work down the street so on weekdays, if you go around 11am, you're perfectly ahead of the noontime rush, and will be seated right away. You can also always do a pickup order, if you don't care to dine within. Food is just as good. Also if you're into their crawfish beignets (which everyone should be!), you can grab something similar from their little neighbor shop that sells quick bites.

    The seating inside is a bit cramped, but not too bad. The restaurant is decently maintained in terms of cleanliness. Service is pretty good and decently fast.

    I've come here a few times and have tried a number of items. All of which have been good:
    Eggs Benedict- comes on a biscuit instead of an english muffin and OMG these biscuits are so good. I normally dont like biscuits but I love theirs! Made in house and just deliciously crispy but soft inside, they are the perfect pair with the eggs. I've ordered this with their Fried Chicken, which you can't go wrong with. And also their Pulled Pork which was tender and seasoned well.
    Beignet Flight- Their sweet beignets are a pretty good treat if you're craving dessert, but their crawfish beignets steal the show. Even though sometimes it can have a slightly strong seafood taste, the cajun spices are so savory, and the exterior dough so comforting. The crawfish beignets are such a treat, and so unique to this restaurant, you have to order them everytime you come!
    Hangtown Fry- Worth trying once for the oysters, but I wouldn't order it again. The oysters kinda give an off taste to the dish and its overall not too pleasing. Too fishy, I guess?
    Not sure if its on the menu anymore, but I have also tried their Gumbo and it was nothing special. you can skip this.

    Brenda's French Soul Food has been on my radar for a while and I'm so glad I finally got a chance to dine here this past weekend.  My boyfriend and I went to the city to visit my cousin and his girlfriend, and we opted to have a late lunch here.

    We arrived around 1:15pm and added our name for a table for 4 on the chalkboard waitlist.  We asked for some menus to decide on what we wanted while we waited and hung out outside until our group was called.  After about a 25 minute wait, we were seated, and our orders were taken soon after since we let our waitress know that we were ready to order.

    Our drinks (watermelon sweet tea and molasses iced coffee) came out really quickly, along with iced waters for everyone.  Not long after, our order came:
    - Shrimp & grits
    - Fried chicken eggs benedict
    - Molasses pork chop special (eggs over medium)
    - Crawfish beignets

    We all shared and sampled each other's orders, and I can honestly say that I couldn't pick a favorite - they were all so delicious!  I definitely understand the hype.  Everything tasted really fresh and packed full of flavor.  I'd highly recommend the visit here, although I'd suggest visiting during an in-between meal time to lessen the wait time.  Also keep in mind - this restaurant isn't super huge inside, so it's probably not ideal for larger groups.  Most of the parties dining around us were groups of 2 or 3.  All in all, a great stop for brunch/lunch for delicious food!

    7/28/2019

    7 photos

    7/27/19

    I think pretty much every other day in my Yelp feed I see someone's pics or review of this place.  Why did it take me so goddam long to come???... I got no excuse.  But, hey, I did, and I tell you, the hype is real, and absolutely deserved!

    Yeah, I've been to 'Nawlins (a few times even) and got fatter.  Definitely fatter.  So the food's good and all, but Brenda's makes the stuff so much easier to eat for those that don't wanna get diabetes or die of a heart attack, or before being able to blind people with the solar reflector your male pattern baldness could be.

    Don't get me wrong, if you eat this crap every day you're still gonna die before your friends, but... at least you're gonna live longer in bliss...

    1. Community Coffee with Chicory $3:  K, so I've only had coffee with chicory maybe at most a couple times in my life, so I dunno if I'm qualified to judge this one, but all I can say it has a very interesting taste with powerful flavors at first, though not bitter.  But give it a few seconds, cause the finish is bitter as f.  Quite the experience.  8/10?

    2. Grandma's Molasses-Black Walnut Iced Coffee $5 "with whipped cream":  And like the hot coffee, definitely interesting.  It's certainly sweet, as you'd expect, but there some good complexity going on in there.  There's of course a very small hint of walnut, but the molasses adds the sweetness that balances with the slightly acidic fruity flavors.  I liked it.  8/10

    3. Beignet Flight $12 "can't decide? try a sampling of each! four per order"...

    3a. Plain "for the die-hard traditionalist":  Alright, so we gotta compare with the standard: Cafe Du Monde's.  Besides the obvious, being Brenda's is not absolutely encased in sugar, I remember Du Monde's being stretchier, a bit chewier, and airier (check out my pics for the place, including one where we stretch one apart--quite impressive.)  But that's not to say Brenda's is bad.  Oh no!... it's delicious!  Moist, slightly denser, and with a great savory and slightly crisp crust.  Definitely technically great.  9/10

    3b. Chocolate "filled with molten Ghirardelli chocolate":  So, the rest of the beignets we had follow the same formula: the same dough and cooking, same flesh and crisp finish, except the dough only serves to surround the filling, which takes up 80%ish of the total volume.  In this case, sure enough, that's some really insanely INTENSE bloody chocolate!  DAMN.  Dark, supremely concentrated... thick, cause thick is the way we all like it, most of the times... alright, I gotta say, that thick and dark ain't my thing, but maybe it's yours...  9/10

    3c. Granny Smith Apple "sweetened with cinnamon-honey butter":  This was the only variation I didn't like.  Despite what their description implies, this thing is barely sweet.  Don't expect anything like your mom's apple pie here with oozing goodness.  It just ain't that.  5/10

    3d. Crawfish "spiced with cayenne, scallions & cheddar":  GENIUS.  Fried dough.  Creamy seafood.  Cheese.  Did I say FRIED?  Yup.  Lucky there ain't no Brenda's in San Jose cause I'd just eat these everyday, ...and die.  10/10

    4. Shrimp & Grits $17 "sauteed shrimp, cheddar grits, spicy tomato-bacon gravy":  Ah, and so finally a quintessential 'Nawlins dish!--and I think the chef is most in her element with this one.  Starting with the grits, they're almost kinda soupy.  this ain't no Roscoe's grits.  And it probably ain't like most grits you've had--only naturally creamy, with all the flavor coming from that red sauce.  And that red sauce--it's remarkably NOT oily!  Like you almost cannot see any grease whatsoever.  It's almost inevitable there's a film of orange oil (we're not eating Szechuan are we???), but Brenda's is remarkably CLEAN.  And interesting thing though, the sauce is sweet. I dunno how I feel about that, but anyway... it's different and not offensive in that way.

    So, you look at that dish and go... wtf... I see like... 2, maybe 3 shrimps poking through?  Well, after I start diving in, I tell you, the shrimp is ENDLESS!  Personally I think the plating is just too understated in how all the shrimp is hidden underneath... all that PERFECTLY cooked shrimp.  Not dry, not stringy, still a bit translucent and crunchy.  Yummy!

    This has got to be the least greasy, most wholesome shrimp and grits I've ever had, yet somehow it's still rich as f.  A gastronomic miracle.  10/10

    5. Chicken, Sausage & Okra Gumbo (Cup) $6:  And like the shrimp & grits, that wholesome-homesome shows through here too.  The "soup" is slightly less thick than what you'll find elsewhere, and the seasoning is definitely far more tame, yet everything seems just right and balanced.  The chicken is in big chunks, and NOT DRY.  Everything's just so CLEAN..... almost refreshingly simple and light!  For a gumbo!!!  10/10

    I cannot wait to come back, but definitely for dinner!

    5/5

    I've heard all great things about Brenda's and finally had a chance to check it out yesterday. Don't let the long line intimidate you, just walk right in and write your name and number of your party down on the chalk board. The wait for us was about close to an hour and luckily, we were waiting inside (they had a small seating area with 4 chairs so grab it FAST)

    While waiting, I got to enjoy the decor and read their specials on the walls. If you aren't picky, you can be seat faster, but we want a table so we waited.

    Our orders:
    * Plain beignets (3 pieces) $6
    * Chocolate beignets (3 pieces) $9 - They use Ghirardelli chocolate which is super rich!
    * One of the House favorites - Chicken, Sausage and Okra Gumbo $6 for a small cup which is perfect for one person
    * Two Eggs Anyway You Like 'Em $9.75 with a side of Andouille $4.25
    * 2 lattes

    The beignets were delicious. Although the chocolate ones were super rich so better share 'em with people so you don't feel super overwhelm with chocolate! The coffee is meh, tasted like burnt coffee which was really unfortunate. The milk option is kinda limited, just regular milk and soy. No biggie since the food was so good. The service was pretty neat and the staff was very friendly. Wish the wait time could have been shorter, but I get it this place is popular. Will definitely come back again soon to try something else on the menu!
